{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_27","type":"command_execution","command":"/run/current-system/sw/bin/bash -lc \"rg -n \\\"cellDeps\\\\.connect|connect\\\\?\\\\.\\\\(\\\" node_modules/@kolu/surface/src/server.ts | head -20; nl -ba node_modules/@kolu/surface/src/server.ts | sed -n '1490,1585p'; rg -n \\\"dispose\\\" node_modules/@kolu/surface/src/server.ts | tail -30\"","aggregated_output":"  1490\t    // serving store here — seeded from the facade's `get` (the node's current level) —\n  1491\t    // and drives it exclusively through the `connect` seam below, so `cellHandlers.get`\n  1492\t    // and `ctxApply` read/write this closure-private store, never anything on the dep.\n  1493\t    // A non-derived cell uses its own `store` directly.\n  1494\t    const store: CellStore<unknown> = isDerivedCellDeps(cellDeps)\n  1495\t      ? inMemoryStore(cellDeps.store.get())\n  1496\t      : cellDeps.store;\n  1497\t    const handlers = cellHandlers(\n  1498\t      // biome-ignore lint/suspicious/noExplicitAny: descriptor is type-discriminator only at runtime\n  1499\t      (surface.descriptors.cells as any)[key] as Cell<string, unknown>,\n  1500\t      {\n  1501\t        store,\n  1502\t        bus,\n  1503\t        patch: patchFn,\n  1504\t        equals: equalsFn,\n  1505\t        onMutate: cellDeps.onMutate,\n  1506\t        onWrite: onWriteFn,\n  1507\t        forward: cellDeps.forward,\n  1508\t        hasSnapshot: cellDeps.hasSnapshot,\n  1509\t      },\n  1510\t    );\n  1511\t\n  1512\t    // Server-internal `ctx.cells.<key>.set/patch` — same dedup/onWrite\n  1513\t    // gates as the wire-facing handlers so an internal write goes\n  1514\t    // through the same atomicity contract (e.g. an in-app\n  1515\t    // `setSavedSession` cancels the autosave timer via `onWrite`, and\n  1516\t    // a no-op republish is suppressed by `equals`).\n  1517\t    //\n  1518\t    // Intentionally does NOT call `onMutate`: that hook is the\n  1519\t    // wire-only client-action audit point, scoped to `set`/`patch`\n  1520\t    // verbs. Server-internal callers are domain code and don't have\n  1521\t    // a meaningful \"patch payload before merge\" to log — they already\n  1522\t    // know what they're writing.\n  1523\t    //\n  1524\t    // Mirrors the equals→onWrite→store.set→bus.publish sequence in\n  1525\t    // `cellHandlers.applyAndPublish`. Kept duplicated rather than\n  1526\t    // extracted to a shared helper so the two paths diverge loudly\n  1527\t    // (TypeScript errors / test failures) if anyone adds a step to\n  1528\t    // only one side. (`store` — resolved above — is a derived cell's private\n  1529\t    // writable backing, or a non-derived cell's own store.)\n  1530\t    // `force` bypasses the `equals` dedup for ONE write — a re-serve's rebind epoch\n  1531\t    // uses it so a fresh spawn re-confirming a value EQUAL to the pre-drain one still\n  1532\t    // republishes, letting a downstream holder tell \"rebound and confirmed\" from\n  1533\t    // \"stale\" (#1681; `reServeSurface`'s cell fold). Steady-state dedup is unchanged:\n  1534\t    // only the explicit `force` caller opts out, per write.\n  1535\t    function ctxApply(next: unknown, opts?: CellCtxSetOpts): void {\n  1536\t      if (!opts?.force && equalsFn?.(store.get(), next)) return;\n  1537\t      onWriteFn?.(next);\n  1538\t      store.set(next);\n  1539\t      bus.publish(next);\n  1540\t    }\n  1541\t    // The write arm (`set`/`patch`) as its own object. The `connect` seam gets it\n  1542\t    // PRIVATELY (below) so the graph — a derived cell's ONE writer — can push\n  1543\t    // through the member's write gate, WITHOUT that setter also landing on the\n  1544\t    // procedure-handler-visible `ctx.cells.<key>`.\n  1545\t    const writeArm = {\n  1546\t      set: ctxApply,\n  1547\t      ...(patchFn\n  1548\t        ? {\n  1549\t            patch: (p: unknown) => {\n  1550\t              ctxApply(patchFn(store.get(), p));\n  1551\t            },\n  1552\t          }\n  1553\t        : {}),\n  1554\t    };\n  1555\t    // A derived cell is wire-read-only AND server-internal-read-only: the graph\n  1556\t    // is its one writer, and it reaches the store ONLY through `connect` (the\n  1557\t    // private `writeArm` below). So a derived cell's `ctx.cells.<key>` exposes `get`\n  1558\t    // plus a THROWING `set`/`patch` — a fail-fast one-writer guard, not a live write\n  1559\t    // path. Keeping the setters PRESENT (throwing) rather than absent makes the ctx\n  1560\t    // TYPE honest: `CellCtxFor` promises `set`/`patch`, and a procedure handler that\n  1561\t    // calls one gets a loud \"graph-owned (one writer)\" error, never a second writer\n  1562\t    // publishing a value the graph never derived and never a bare \"set is not a\n  1563\t    // function\". Non-derived cells keep their real server-internal writers.\n  1564\t    const derivedWriteGuard = (): never => {\n  1565\t      throw new Error(\n  1566\t        `implementSurface: cell \"${key}\" is graph-owned (a derived cell) — the graph is its one writer; ctx.cells.${key}.set/patch is not a write path.`,\n  1567\t      );\n  1568\t    };\n  1569\t    cellsCtx[key] = isDerivedCellDeps(cellDeps)\n  1570\t      ? {\n  1571\t          get: () => store.get(),\n  1572\t          set: derivedWriteGuard,\n  1573\t          ...(patchFn ? { patch: derivedWriteGuard } : {}),\n  1574\t        }\n  1575\t      : { get: () => store.get(), ...writeArm };\n  1576\t\n  1577\t    // Optional async-source republish: fire once after the cell ctx is\n  1578\t    // wired, handing it the PRIVATE write arm so a late-arriving value (and a\n  1579\t    // derived cell's graph pushes) flows through the same\n  1580\t    // equals/onWrite/store.set/bus.publish path — without exposing `set` on a\n  1581\t    // derived cell's public ctx.\n  1582\t    const cd = cellDeps as {\n  1583\t      connect?: (c: { set: (v: unknown) => void }) => void | Promise<void>;\n  1584\t    };\n  1585\t    if (cd.connect) void cd.connect(writeArm);\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_28","type":"agent_message","text":"{\"approved\":false,\"summary\":\"The agent→parent→browser alert flow is coherent, typechecks cleanly, and the 34 targeted alert/metrics/history/agent tests pass. However, first-time notification enablement is effectively broken on browsers requiring a user gesture, and there are several smaller correctness and lifecycle issues. The full suite was not clean in this read-only environment: temporary-directory tests hit EROFS and one unchanged process-stream test failed.\",\"findings\":[{\"id\":\"F1\",\"severity\":\"major\",\"location\":\"packages/app/src/client/App.tsx:557\",\"issue\":\"Notification permission is requested automatically during component initialization, outside a user gesture. Browsers commonly suppress or reject such requests. Since `notify.show` is explicitly a no-op until permission is granted and there is no later user-triggered permission path, first-time users can receive no OS alerts at all.\",\"suggestion\":\"Add an explicit “Enable notifications” control and call `notify.requestPermission()` from its click handler. Surface denied/unsupported status so users understand why notifications are inactive.\",\"status\":\"open\"},{\"id\":\"F2\",\"severity\":\"minor\",\"location\":\"packages/app/src/client/App.tsx:587\",\"issue\":\"The promises returned by `setAppBadge` and `clearAppBadge` are discarded without rejection handling. Feature presence does not guarantee success; security, permission, or document-state failures can therefore produce unhandled promise rejections whenever this effect runs.\",\"suggestion\":\"Route both operations through a small async helper with `try/catch`, or attach `.catch(...)` while preserving the unsupported-API no-op.\",\"status\":\"open\"},{\"id\":\"F3\",\"severity\":\"minor\",\"location\":\"packages/app/src/client/App.tsx:760\",\"issue\":\"The host-card alert count reads the raw cell without considering entry liveness. Cell subscriptions retain their last value across a dropped link, so a disconnected host continues showing an undimmed red “N alerts” indicator even though the badge correctly excludes that same stale value. This presents stale state as a live alert.\",\"suggestion\":\"Gate the count on `entry.state().kind === \\\"connected\\\"`, or explicitly render a visually stale/last-known indicator when disconnected.\",\"status\":\"open\"},{\"id\":\"F4\",\"severity\":\"nit\",\"location\":\"packages/common/src/alerts.ts:106\",\"issue\":\"`alertsEqual` is not true set equality when either array contains duplicates. Equal array lengths plus one-way membership can consider `{items:[\\\"cpu\\\",\\\"mem\\\"]}` equal to `{items:[\\\"cpu\\\",\\\"cpu\\\"]}`. The current producer emits unique IDs, but the schema and exported function do not enforce that invariant.\",\"suggestion\":\"Compare two `Set`s including their sizes, or enforce uniqueness in `AlertsSchema` and document that precondition explicitly.\",\"status\":\"open\"},{\"id\":\"F5\",\"severity\":\"nit\",\"location\":\"packages/agent/src/main.ts:193\",\"issue\":\"The lifecycle commentary says `emitMetrics` remains null until the derived cell's connect effect subscribes. In the pinned reactor implementation, `scan(...)` subscribes to the source synchronously during construction, before `derived.cell` connects, so this explanation of the guard and pre-connect behavior is incorrect.\",\"suggestion\":\"Update both this comment and the corresponding tick comment around line 317 to explain that `scan` installs the emitter synchronously and that it becomes null only after scan/source teardown.\",\"status\":\"open\"}],\"responseToRebuttal\":\"\"}"}}
